\subsection{Geometric Features of the 4D Phase Space}
\label{subsec:geometry}

When analyzing this mathematical system, the geometric structures shift from previous lower-dimensional derivations in three important ways:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{The Critical Manifold $\mathcal{M}_0$:} Defined strictly in the limit $\varepsilon \to 0$ by setting the fast equation to zero: $\mathcal{F}(e,U,V,T_s)=0$. On the active turbulent branch, $e+\delta = (l_0\Delta)^2$ where $\Delta = \eta\,\gamma\,(U^2+V^2)-K\,G(T_s)$, so $e^* = (l_0\Delta)^2-\delta$.
    \item \textbf{The Admissibility Threshold:} The active branch exists only when $e^* \ge 0$, equivalently when $|\Delta| \ge \sqrt{\delta}/l_0$; under the positive-branch assumption this becomes $\Delta \ge \sqrt{\delta}/l_0$. In the present closure, regime transition still occurs by crossing the physical boundary at $e=0$.
    \item \textbf{The Regularized Laminar Floor:} For trajectories driven toward weak turbulence, the full numerical model uses a smooth floor limiter near $e=-\delta$ so that the drag and heat-exchange closures remain well-defined and the state stays in the admissible background-mixing regime. Because $U^2 + V^2$ is rotationally symmetric, the active branch has circular paraboloid geometry in the $(U, V, e)$ coordinates for fixed $T_s$.
\end{enumerate}